    <item>
      <title>Black Wind</title>
      <link>https://blog.jverkamp.com/2020/03/31/black-wind/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://blog.jverkamp.com/2020/03/31/black-wind/</guid>
      <description>&lt;figure class=&#34;cover-image&#34;&gt;
                &lt;a data-goodreads-type=&#34;book&#34; data-goodreads-id=&#34;41696&#34; href=&#34;https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41696.black-wind&#34;&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://blog.jverkamp.com/embeds/books/black-wind.jpg&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;After 18 of these, they&amp;rsquo;re starting to sound awfully familiar. Basically, combine a bit of the Japanese influence from &lt;a data-goodreads-type=&#34;book&#34; data-goodreads-id=&#34;41694&#34; href=&#34;https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41694.dragon&#34;&gt;Dragon&lt;/a&gt; and a bit of the mysterious deaths on islands from &lt;a data-goodreads-type=&#34;book&#34; data-goodreads-id=&#34;41704&#34; href=&#34;https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41704.shock-wave&#34;&gt;Shock Wave&lt;/a&gt; and you have &lt;a data-goodreads-type=&#34;book&#34; data-goodreads-id=&#34;41696&#34; href=&#34;https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41696.black-wind&#34;&gt;Black Wind&lt;/a&gt;. Doesn&amp;rsquo;t make it bad by any stretch of the imagination&amp;hellip; just samey.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I think the crazies part of listening to this book was doing so while on lockdown from COVID-19. It&amp;rsquo;s not quite as bad as a weaponized smallpox by a long shot, but Cussler&amp;rsquo;s descriptions of the world shutting down, health facilities and morgues being overloaded was disturbingly prescient. Given that he passed in February, before the full extent of what was coming had really hit the United States, I wonder if he could have imagination it coming to life.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Split a file with headers</title>
      <link>https://blog.jverkamp.com/2020/03/30/split-a-file-with-headers/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://blog.jverkamp.com/2020/03/30/split-a-file-with-headers/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;I have a bunch of files with Arabic content that I need to split into chunks so they can be better run in parallel&lt;sup class=&#34;footnote-ref&#34; id=&#34;fnref:iknow&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#fn:iknow&#34;&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;. But by default, when I open them in a text editor, the encoding changes from &lt;code&gt;windows-1256&lt;/code&gt; to &lt;code&gt;utf-8&lt;/code&gt;&lt;sup class=&#34;footnote-ref&#34; id=&#34;fnref:iknow2&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#fn:iknow2&#34;&gt;2&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;. I could use the Unix &lt;code&gt;split&lt;/code&gt; command to break them into chunks, but I need to preserve the headers. So&amp;hellip; how do I fix all this?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Write a script!&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
